@NODE Gen "Using QuickConv/General"

@{b}Starting & quitting the program@{ub}
@{b}-------------------------------@{ub}

    To start the program just doubleclick it's icon from Workbench. To quit you
have three possibilities: Click the close gadget of QuickConv window; Select
'Quit' from the menu; Press rightcommand-q.

@{b}The GUI@{ub}
@{b}-------@{ub}

    The GUI of QuickConv is very simple. The window is divided in two parts: the
Value part and the Operators part.

    In the Value part there are three fields named Hex, Dec and Bin which will
contain the three formats of the number.

    In the Operators part there are six gadgets and two fields which are:

- '<<' this gadget is used to left-shift the number contained in 'Value' (in
the three fields) of the quantity contained in 'Number'.

- '>>' this gadget is used to right-shift the number contained in 'Value' (in
the three fields) of the quantity contained in 'Number'.

- 'Number' this field is used to set shift size. It has to be expressed in
decimal format.

- '&' this gadget is used to perform an AND operation between the number
contained in 'Buf' and the current number in 'Value'.

- '|' this gadget is used to perform an Inclusive OR  operation between the    
number contained in 'Buf' and the current number in 'Value'.

- '^' this gadget is used to perform an Exclusive OR  operation between the
number contained in 'Buf' and the current number in 'Value'.

- '~' this gadget is used to perform the complement of the number contained in 
'Buf'.

- 'Buf' this field contains a number used by operators and expressed always in
the Binary format.

    To better understand how to work with Operators see @{"here" LINK Op}.

    The menus contain only the voices About and Quit. I think they don't need
explaination.

@{b}About the strings@{ub}
@{b}-----------------@{ub}

    A number of simple, keyboard driven editing functions are available for the
string fileds (Hex,Bin,Dec,Number and Buf).These editing functions are shown in 
the following table.

             Key              Function
             ---              --------
                 <-   Cursor to previous character.

           Shift <-   Cursor to beginning of string.

                 ->   Cursor to next character.

           Shift ->   Cursor to end of string.

                Del   Delete the character under the cursor.

          Shift Del   Delete from the character under the cursor to the
                      end of the line.

          Backspace   Delete the character to left of cursor.

    Shift Backspace   Delete from the character to the left of the
                      cursor to the start of the line.

    Return or Enter   Terminate input.

      Right Amiga Q   Undo (cancel) the last editing change to the
                      string.

@{b}Converting numbers@{ub}
@{b}------------------@{ub}

    To convert a number just insert it in one of the three fields of 'Value'.
Automatically it will be converted in the other two formats.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} if you want to enter a binary number it's not necessary to write all the
32 bits, simply enter the necessary ones. Eg. for the number 2(Dec) enter '10'.
This is true also for 'Buf'.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Op "Using QuickConv/Operators"

@{b}Using Operators@{ub}
@{b}---------------@{ub}

    The three operators @{b}And, Inclusive Or and Exclusive Or@{ub} work in the same
manner. They perform this operation:

    Result = 'Buf' -operator- 'Value'

and the Result is diplayed in the three 'Value' fields.

NOTE: whenever you enter a new number in the 'Value' fields, the old one will be
copied to the 'Buf' field. Using QuickConv you'll find this very convenient.

Example:

    You know the value (Bin, Dec or Hex, it doesn't matter) of three numbers:
N1, N2, N3 and you want to perform this operation:

    (N1 & N2) | N3

You have to proceed this way:

- Enter N1 in 'Value'
- Enter N2 in 'Value'. N1 will be automatically copied in 'Buf'.
- Click on the '&' gadget. 'Value' will contain the result of this operation.
- Enter N3 in 'Value'. The result of N1&N2 will be automatically copied in 'Buf'.
- Click on the '|' gadget.

The final result is displayed in 'Value'

    The @{b}Shift Operators@{ub} require a non null value in 'Number' field. They perform
a shift of the number contained in 'Value' using the quantity contained in
'Number':

    Result = 'Value' -l/rshift- 'Number'

the Result is diplayed in 'Value'. Note: 'Number' must be in Decimal format.

Example:

    You have to perform 4<<8:

- Enter 4 in the Dec field of 'Value'.
- Enter 8 in the (Dec) filed 'Number'
- Click '<<' gadget.

    The @{b}Complement Operator@{ub} performs the complement of the binary
number contained in 'Buf'. The result is displayed in the three fields of
'Value'.

Example:

    You want to know the complement of the number 17.

- Enter 17 in the Dec field of 'Value'
- Copy the bin value to 'Buf' or, better, click in a field of 'Value' and press
  Return, this will automatically copy the value to 'Buf'.
- Click on the gadget '~'.

If you knew the binary value of 17 you could enter it directly in the 'Buf'
field and click '~' gadget, of course.


